One of the Adara community development association leaders, Mr Awemi Dio Maisamari, has presented the position of the ethnic nationality at the  Kachia, Kajuru and Chikun Judicial Commission Of Inquiry hearing in Kaduna. Maisamari linked the crisis in Kachia, Kajuru and Chikun local government area of Kaduna State from 2017-2019 to leadership failure. He disclosed this while being cross examined at the ongoing Judicial Commission of inquiry into the crisis in the three local government areas within the period under review. He described leadership failure in the state as a major factor responsible for the escalation of the crisis across the surrounding communities. “Leadership failure is a major factor in the situation we found ourselves. The crisis can be traceable to leadership failure and this is our belief as  Adara people,” he said. He further added that the crisis in these local government areas goes beyond security and terrorism which the commission is trying to look at as he recommended  ‎that the commission should focus on the remote causes which include political, economic and other factors captured in their memo. The group also expressed concern that the system does not provide a level playing ground for tribes like Adara to compete with other tribes despite their population. He also said that they hoped that at the end of the hearing there would be solution to the crisis. ‎Another elder in Kajuru, Usman Danlami, listed some of the villages attacked to include Unguwar Barde, Koramai, Dogon Noma, Chikwale, Kwasau Lagede, Banono and Unguwar Bura among others. LEADERSHIP recalls that the state governor, Nasir El-Rufai set up the 12-man commission of inquiry into the incessant communal crisis in the three LGAs under the chairmanship of Justice Isa Aliyu  to find a lasting solution to the killings and attacks that took place in the area from 2017 to 2019.